===Etymology===
{{etyl|enm}} {{term|chirche|lang=enm}} < {{etyl|ang}} {{term|ċiriċe|lang=ang||church}}, from [[w:West Germanic|West Germanic]] *{{term||kirika}}, from {{etyl|grc}} {{term|κυριακόν|tr=kuriakon|lang=grc|sc=polytonic}}, neuter form of {{term|κυριακός||belonging to the lord|lang=grc|sc=polytonic}} from {{term|κύριος|tr=kurios||ruler, lord|lang=grc|sc=polytonic}}. For vowel evolution, see {{term|bury}}. Greek {{term|κυριακόν|tr=kuriakon|lang=grc|sc=polytonic}} was used of houses of Christian worship since circa 300 AD, especially in the East, though it was less common in this sense than {{term|ἐκκλησία||congregation|tr=ekklēsia|lang=grc|sc=polytonic}} or {{term|βασιλική||royal thing|tr=basilikē|lang=grc|sc=polytonic}}. An example of the direct Greek-to-Germanic progress of many Christian words, via the [[w:Goths|Goths]]; it was probably used by West Germanic people in their pre-Christian period. Also picked up by [[Slavic]], via Old High German {{term|chirihha|lang=goh}} (compare Old Church Slavonic {{term|sc=Cyrl|црькъі|tr=crĭky|lang=cu}}, Russian {{term|sc=Cyrl|церковь|tr=cérkov’|lang=ru}}). [[w:Romance languages|Romance]] and [[w:Celtic languages|Celtic]] languages use variants of Latin {{term|ecclesia|lang=la}}.

